#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:255
msgid ""
"Note that we told ``metafunc.parametrize()`` that your scenario values "
"should be considered class-scoped.  With pytest-2.3 this leads to a resource-"
"based ordering."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:260
msgid "Deferring the setup of parametrized resources"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:264
msgid ""
"The parametrization of test functions happens at collection time.  It is a "
"good idea to setup expensive resources like DB connections or subprocess "
"only when the actual test is run. Here is a simple example how you can "
"achieve that. This test requires a ``db`` object fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:270
msgid ""
"# content of test_backends.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_db_initialized(db):\n"
"    # a dummy test\n"
"    if db.__class__.__name__ == \"DB2\":\n"
"        pytest.fail(\"deliberately failing for demo purposes\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:282
msgid ""
"We can now add a test configuration that generates two invocations of the "
"``test_db_initialized`` function and also implements a factory that creates "
"a database object for the actual test invocations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:286
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    if \"db\" in metafunc.fixturenames:\n"
"        metafunc.parametrize(\"db\", [\"d1\", \"d2\"], indirect=True)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class DB1:\n"
"    \"one database object\"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class DB2:\n"
"    \"alternative database object\"\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def db(request):\n"
"    if request.param == \"d1\":\n"
"        return DB1()\n"
"    elif request.param == \"d2\":\n"
"        return DB2()\n"
"    else:\n"
"        raise ValueError(\"invalid internal test config\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:314
msgid "Let's first see how it looks like at collection time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:316
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_backends.py --collect-only\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"<Module test_backends.py>\n"
"  <Function test_db_initialized[d1]>\n"
"  <Function test_db_initialized[d2]>\n"
"\n"
"========================== no tests ran in 0.12s ==========================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:330
msgid "And then when we run the test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:332
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q test_backends.py\n"
".F                                                                   [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"_________________________ test_db_initialized[d2] "
"__________________________\n"
"\n"
"db = <conftest.DB2 object at 0xdeadbeef>\n"
"\n"
"    def test_db_initialized(db):\n"
"        # a dummy test\n"
"        if db.__class__.__name__ == \"DB2\":\n"
">           pytest.fail(\"deliberately failing for demo purposes\")\n"
"E           Failed: deliberately failing for demo purposes\n"
"\n"
"test_backends.py:8: Failed\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_backends.py::test_db_initialized[d2] - Failed: deliberately "
"f...\n"
"1 failed, 1 passed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:352
msgid ""
"The first invocation with ``db == \"DB1\"`` passed while the second with "
"``db == \"DB2\"`` failed.  Our ``db`` fixture function has instantiated each "
"of the DB values during the setup phase while the ``pytest_generate_tests`` "
"generated two according calls to the ``test_db_initialized`` during the "
"collection phase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:357
msgid "Apply indirect on particular arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:359
msgid ""
"Very often parametrization uses more than one argument name. There is "
"opportunity to apply ``indirect`` parameter on particular arguments. It can "
"be done by passing list or tuple of arguments' names to ``indirect``. In the "
"example below there is a function ``test_indirect`` which uses two fixtures: "
"``x`` and ``y``. Here we give to indirect the list, which contains the name "
"of the fixture ``x``. The indirect parameter will be applied to this "
"argument only, and the value ``a`` will be passed to respective fixture "
"function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:366
msgid ""
"# content of test_indirect_list.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"function\")\n"
"def x(request):\n"
"    return request.param * 3\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"function\")\n"
"def y(request):\n"
"    return request.param * 2\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"x, y\", [(\"a\", \"b\")], indirect=[\"x\"])\n"
"def test_indirect(x, y):\n"
"    assert x == \"aaa\"\n"
"    assert y == \"b\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:388
msgid "The result of this test will be successful:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:390
msgid ""
"$ pytest test_indirect_list.py --collect-only\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"<Module test_indirect_list.py>\n"
"  <Function test_indirect[a-b]>\n"
"\n"
"========================== no tests ran in 0.12s ==========================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:406
msgid "Parametrizing test methods through per-class configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:411
msgid ""
"Here is an example ``pytest_generate_tests`` function implementing a "
"parametrization scheme similar to Michael Foord's `unittest parametrizer`_ "
"but in a lot less code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:415
msgid ""
"# content of ./test_parametrize.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_generate_tests(metafunc):\n"
"    # called once per each test function\n"
"    funcarglist = metafunc.cls.params[metafunc.function.__name__]\n"
"    argnames = sorted(funcarglist[0])\n"
"    metafunc.parametrize(\n"
"        argnames, [[funcargs[name] for name in argnames] for funcargs in "
"funcarglist]\n"
"    )\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class TestClass:\n"
"    # a map specifying multiple argument sets for a test method\n"
"    params = {\n"
"        \"test_equals\": [dict(a=1, b=2), dict(a=3, b=3)],\n"
"        \"test_zerodivision\": [dict(a=1, b=0)],\n"
"    }\n"
"\n"
"    def test_equals(self, a, b):\n"
"        assert a == b\n"
"\n"
"    def test_zerodivision(self, a, b):\n"
"        with pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError):\n"
"            a / b"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:444
msgid ""
"Our test generator looks up a class-level definition which specifies which "
"argument sets to use for each test function.  Let's run it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:447
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q\n"
"F..                                                                  [100%]\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________ TestClass.test_equals[1-2] "
"________________________\n"
"\n"
"self = <test_parametrize.TestClass object at 0xdeadbeef>, a = 1, b = 2\n"
"\n"
"    def test_equals(self, a, b):\n"
">       assert a == b\n"
"E       assert 1 == 2\n"
"\n"
"test_parametrize.py:21: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_parametrize.py::TestClass::test_equals[1-2] - assert 1 == 2\n"
"1 failed, 2 passed in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:466
msgid "Indirect parametrization with multiple fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:468
msgid ""
"Here is a stripped down real-life example of using parametrized testing for "
"testing serialization of objects between different python interpreters.  We "
"define a ``test_basic_objects`` function which is to be run with different "
"sets of arguments for its three arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:473
msgid ""
"``python1``: first python interpreter, run to pickle-dump an object to a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:474
msgid ""
"``python2``: second interpreter, run to pickle-load an object from a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:475
msgid "``obj``: object to be dumped/loaded"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:477
msgid ""
"\"\"\"\n"
"module containing a parametrized tests testing cross-python\n"
"serialization via the pickle module.\n"
"\"\"\"\n"
"import shutil\n"
"import subprocess\n"
"import textwrap\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"pythonlist = [\"python3.5\", \"python3.6\", \"python3.7\"]\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=pythonlist)\n"
"def python1(request, tmpdir):\n"
"    picklefile = tmpdir.join(\"data.pickle\")\n"
"    return Python(request.param, picklefile)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(params=pythonlist)\n"
"def python2(request, python1):\n"
"    return Python(request.param, python1.picklefile)\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Python:\n"
"    def __init__(self, version, picklefile):\n"
"        self.pythonpath = shutil.which(version)\n"
"        if not self.pythonpath:\n"
"            pytest.skip(\"{!r} not found\".format(version))\n"
"        self.picklefile = picklefile\n"
"\n"
"    def dumps(self, obj):\n"
"        dumpfile = self.picklefile.dirpath(\"dump.py\")\n"
"        dumpfile.write(\n"
"            textwrap.dedent(\n"
"                r\"\"\"\n"
"                import pickle\n"
"                f = open({!r}, 'wb')\n"
"                s = pickle.dump({!r}, f, protocol=2)\n"
"                f.close()\n"
"                \"\"\".format(\n"
"                    str(self.picklefile), obj\n"
"                )\n"
"            )\n"
"        )\n"
"        subprocess.check_call((self.pythonpath, str(dumpfile)))\n"
"\n"
"    def load_and_is_true(self, expression):\n"
"        loadfile = self.picklefile.dirpath(\"load.py\")\n"
"        loadfile.write(\n"
"            textwrap.dedent(\n"
"                r\"\"\"\n"
"                import pickle\n"
"                f = open({!r}, 'rb')\n"
"                obj = pickle.load(f)\n"
"                f.close()\n"
"                res = eval({!r})\n"
"                if not res:\n"
"                    raise SystemExit(1)\n"
"                \"\"\".format(\n"
"                    str(self.picklefile), expression\n"
"                )\n"
"            )\n"
"        )\n"
"        print(loadfile)\n"
"        subprocess.check_call((self.pythonpath, str(loadfile)))\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"obj\", [42, {}, {1: 3}])\n"
"def test_basic_objects(python1, python2, obj):\n"
"    python1.dumps(obj)\n"
"    python2.load_and_is_true(\"obj == {}\".format(obj))\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:479
msgid ""
"Running it results in some skips if we don't have all the python "
"interpreters installed and otherwise runs all combinations (3 interpreters "
"times 3 interpreters times 3 objects to serialize/deserialize):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:481
msgid ""
". $ pytest -rs -q multipython.py\n"
"ssssssssssss......sss......                                          [100%]\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"SKIPPED [15] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/CWD/multipython.py:29: 'python3.5' not found\n"
"12 passed, 15 skipped in 0.12s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:490
msgid "Indirect parametrization of optional implementations/imports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:492
msgid ""
"If you want to compare the outcomes of several implementations of a given "
"API, you can write test functions that receive the already imported "
"implementations and get skipped in case the implementation is not importable/"
"available.  Let's say we have a \"base\" implementation and the other "
"(possibly optimized ones) need to provide similar results:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:498
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\")\n"
"def basemod(request):\n"
"    return pytest.importorskip(\"base\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\", params=[\"opt1\", \"opt2\"])\n"
"def optmod(request):\n"
"    return pytest.importorskip(request.param)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:514
msgid "And then a base implementation of a simple function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:516
msgid ""
"# content of base.py\n"
"def func1():\n"
"    return 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:522
msgid "And an optimized version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:524
msgid ""
"# content of opt1.py\n"
"def func1():\n"
"    return 1.0001"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:530
msgid "And finally a little test module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:532
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_func1(basemod, optmod):\n"
"    assert round(basemod.func1(), 3) == round(optmod.func1(), 3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:541
msgid "If you run this with reporting for skips enabled:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:543
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rs test_module.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py .s                                                    [100%]\n"
"\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"SKIPPED [1] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/conftest.py:12: could not import 'opt2': No "
"module named 'opt2'\n"
"======================= 1 passed, 1 skipped in 0.12s ======================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:558
msgid ""
"You'll see that we don't have an ``opt2`` module and thus the second test "
"run of our ``test_func1`` was skipped.  A few notes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:561
msgid ""
"the fixture functions in the ``conftest.py`` file are \"session-scoped\" "
"because we don't need to import more than once"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:564
msgid ""
"if you have multiple test functions and a skipped import, you will see the "
"``[1]`` count increasing in the report"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:567
msgid ""
"you can put :ref:`@pytest.mark.parametrize <@pytest.mark.parametrize>` style "
"parametrization on the test functions to parametrize input/output values as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:573
msgid "Set marks or test ID for individual parametrized test"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:575
msgid ""
"Use ``pytest.param`` to apply marks or set test ID to individual "
"parametrized test. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:578
msgid ""
"# content of test_pytest_param_example.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    \"test_input,expected\",\n"
"    [\n"
"        (\"3+5\", 8),\n"
"        pytest.param(\"1+7\", 8, marks=pytest.mark.basic),\n"
"        pytest.param(\"2+4\", 6, marks=pytest.mark.basic, "
"id=\"basic_2+4\"),\n"
"        pytest.param(\n"
"            \"6*9\", 42, marks=[pytest.mark.basic, pytest.mark.xfail], "
"id=\"basic_6*9\"\n"
"        ),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_eval(test_input, expected):\n"
"    assert eval(test_input) == expected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:598
msgid ""
"In this example, we have 4 parametrized tests. Except for the first test, we "
"mark the rest three parametrized tests with the custom marker ``basic``, and "
"for the fourth test we also use the built-in mark ``xfail`` to indicate this "
"test is expected to fail. For explicitness, we set test ids for some tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:603
msgid ""
"Then run ``pytest`` with verbose mode and with only the ``basic`` marker:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:605
msgid ""
"$ pytest -v -m basic\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y -- "
"$PYTHON_PREFIX/bin/python\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collecting ... collected 14 items / 11 deselected / 3 selected\n"
"\n"
"test_pytest_param_example.py::test_eval[1+7-8] PASSED                [ 33%]\n"
"test_pytest_param_example.py::test_eval[basic_2+4] PASSED            [ 66%]\n"
"test_pytest_param_example.py::test_eval[basic_6*9] XFAIL             [100%]\n"
"\n"
"=============== 2 passed, 11 deselected, 1 xfailed in 0.12s ================"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:620
msgid "As the result:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:622
msgid "Four tests were collected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:623
msgid "One test was deselected because it doesn't have the ``basic`` mark."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:624
msgid "Three tests with the ``basic`` mark was selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:625
msgid ""
"The test ``test_eval[1+7-8]`` passed, but the name is autogenerated and "
"confusing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:626
msgid "The test ``test_eval[basic_2+4]`` passed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:627
msgid "The test ``test_eval[basic_6*9]`` was expected to fail and did fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:632
msgid "Parametrizing conditional raising"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:634
msgid ""
"Use :func:`pytest.raises` with the :ref:`pytest.mark.parametrize ref` "
"decorator to write parametrized tests in which some tests raise exceptions "
"and others do not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:638
msgid ""
"It is helpful to define a no-op context manager ``does_not_raise`` to serve "
"as a complement to ``raises``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:641
msgid ""
"from contextlib import contextmanager\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@contextmanager\n"
"def does_not_raise():\n"
"    yield\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    \"example_input,expectation\",\n"
"    [\n"
"        (3, does_not_raise()),\n"
"        (2, does_not_raise()),\n"
"        (1, does_not_raise()),\n"
"        (0, pytest.raises(ZeroDivisionError)),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_division(example_input, expectation):\n"
"    \"\"\"Test how much I know division.\"\"\"\n"
"    with expectation:\n"
"        assert (6 / example_input) is not None"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:666
msgid ""
"In the example above, the first three test cases should run unexceptionally, "
"while the fourth should raise ``ZeroDivisionError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:669
msgid ""
"If you're only supporting Python 3.7+, you can simply use ``nullcontext`` to "
"define ``does_not_raise``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:672
msgid "from contextlib import nullcontext as does_not_raise"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:676
msgid "Or, if you're supporting Python 3.3+ you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:678
msgid "from contextlib import ExitStack as does_not_raise"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:682
msgid "Or, if desired, you can ``pip install contextlib2`` and use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/parametrize.rst:684
msgid "from contextlib2 import nullcontext as does_not_raise"
msgstr ""
